\begin_layout Plain Layout
The GO Index is a summary measure for NWP models that is used by the US
 Air Force.
 It combines verification statistics for several forecast variables and
 lead times.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and wind direction statistics.
 Future functionality may include information about time-trends and/or calculati
ons based on climatology (e.g., anomaly correlation).
 This section summarizes the capabilities of the Stat-Analysis tool and
 describes how the GO Index, wind direction, summary statistics, and aggregated
 statistics are computed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Filter STAT lines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
The Stat-Analysis tool can be used to simply filter out specific STAT lines
 based on user-specified search criteria.
 All of the STAT lines that are retained from one or many files are written
 to a single output file.
 The output file for filtered STAT lines must be specified using the
\series bold
 -dump_row
\series medium
 job command option.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Summary statistics for columns
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:StA_Summary-statistics-for"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
The Stat-Analysis tool can be used to produce summary information for columns
 of data.
 After the user specifies the column(s) of interest and any other relevant
 search criteria, summary information is produced from values in those column(s)
 of data.
 The summary statistics produced are: mean, standard deviation, minimum,
 maximum, the 10th, 25th, 50th, 75th, and 90th percentiles, the interquartile
 range, the range, and both weighted and unweighted means using the logic
 prescribed by the World Meteorological Organization (WMO).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
Confidence intervals are computed for the mean and standard deviation of
 the column of data.
 For the mean, the confidence interval is computed two ways - based on an
 assumption of normality and also using the bootstrap method.
 For the standard deviation, the confidence interval is computed using the
 bootstrap method.
 In this application of the bootstrap method, the values in the column of
 data being summarized are resampled, and for each replicated sample, the
 mean and standard deviation are computed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The columns to be summarized can be specified in one of two ways.
 Use the 
\series bold
-line_type
\series default
 option exactly once to specify a single input line type and use the 
\series bold
-column
\series default
 option one or more times to select the columns of data to be summarized.
 Alternatively, use the 
\series bold
-column
\series default
 option one or more times formatting the entries as 
\series bold
LINE_TYPE:COLUMN
\series default
.
 For example, the RMSE column from the CNT line type can be selected using
\series bold
 -line_type CNT -column RMSE 
\series default
or using 
\series bold
-column CNT:RMSE
\series default
.
 With the second option, columns from multiple input line types may be selected.
 For example, 
\series bold
-column CNT:RMSE,CNT:MAE,CTS:CSI
\series default
 select two CNT columns one CTS column.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The WMO mean values are computed in one of three ways, as determined by
 the configuration file settings for 
\series bold
wmo_sqrt_stats
\series default
 and 
\series bold
wmo_fisher_stats
\series default
.
 The statistics listed in the first option are square roots.
 When computing WMO means, the input values are first squared, then averaged,
 and the square root of the average value is reported.
 The statistics listed in the second option are correlations to which the
 Fisher transformation is applied.
 For any statistic not listed, the WMO mean is computed as a simple arithmetic
 mean.
 The 
\series bold
WMO_TYPE
\series default
 output column indicates the method applied (
\series bold
SQRT
\series default
, 
\series bold
FISHER
\series default
, or 
\series bold
MEAN
\series default
).
 The 
\series bold
WMO_MEAN
\series default
 and 
\series bold
WMO_WEIGHTED_MEAN
\series default
 columns contain the unweighted and weighted means, respectively.
 The value listed in the 
\series bold
TOTAL
\series default
 column of each input line is used as the weight.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
-derive
\series default
 job command option can be used to perform the derivation of statistics
 on the fly from input partial sums and contingency table counts.
 When enabled, SL1L2 and SAL1L2 input lines are converted to CNT statistics,
 VL1L2 input lines are converted to VCNT statistics, and CTC lines are converted
 to CTS statistics.
 Users should take care with this option.
 If the data passed to this job contains both partial sums and derived statistic
s, using the 
\series bold
-derive
\series default
 option will effectively cause the statistics to be double counted.
 Use the 
\series bold
-line_type
\series default
 job command option to filter the data passed to Stat-Analysis jobs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Aggregated values from multiple STAT lines
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:StA_Aggregated-values-from"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
The Stat-Analysis tool can be used to create aggregated values from multiple
 STAT lines of the same type.
 The user may specify the specific line type of interest and any other relevant
 search criteria.
 The Stat-Analysis tool then creates sums of each of the values in all lines
 matching the search criteria.
 The aggregated data are output as the same line type as the user specified.
 The STAT line types which may be aggregated in this way are the contingency
 table (FHO, CTC, PCT, MCTC, NBRCTC), partial sums (SL1L2, SAL1L2, VL1L2,
 and VAL1L2), and other (ISC, RHIST, PHIST, RELP, NBRCNT, SSVAR, and GRAD)
 line types.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Aggregate STAT lines and produce aggregated statistics
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:StA_Aggregate-STAT-lines"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
The Stat-Analysis tool can be used to aggregate multiple STAT lines of the
 same type together and produce relevant statistics from the aggregated
 line.
 This may be done in the same manner listed above in 
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:StA_Aggregated-values-from"

\end_inset


\series medium
.
 However, rather than writing out the aggregated STAT line itself, the relevant
 statistics generated from that aggregated line are provided in the output.
 Specifically, if a contingency table line type (FHO, CTC, PCT, MCTC, or
 NBRCTC) has been aggregated, a contingency table statistics (CTS, PSTD,
 MCTS, or NBRCTS) line type will be written out.
 If a partial sums line type (SL1L2 or SAL1L2) has been aggregated, a continuous
 statistics (CNT) line type will be written out.
 If a vector partial sums line type (VL1L2) has been aggregated, the vector
 continuous statistics (VCNT) line type will be written out.
 For ensembles, the ORANK line type can be accumulated into RHIST, PHIST,
 RELP, or SSVAR output.
 If the matched pair line type (MPR) has been aggregated, the user may choose
 the line type to be output (FHO, CTC, CTS, CNT, MCTC, MCTS, SL1L2, SAL1L2,
 VL1L2, VCNT, WDIR, PCT, PSTD, PJC, or PRC).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
When aggregating the matched pair line type (MPR) and computing an output
 contingency table statistics (CTS) or continuous statistics (CNT) line
 type, the bootstrapping method is applied for computing confidence intervals.
 The bootstrapping method is applied here in the same way that it is applied
 in the statistics tools.
 For a set of n matched forecast-observation pairs, the matched pairs are
 resampled with replacement many times.
 For each replicated sample, the corresponding statistics are computed.
 The confidence intervals are derived from the statistics computed for each
 replicated sample.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Skill Score Index, including GO Index 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:StA_Skill-Score-Index,"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series medium
The Stat-Analysis tool can be used to calculate the skill score indices
 by weighting scores for different meteorological fields at different pressure
 levels and for different lead times.
 Specifically, the GO Index can be computed.
 The GO index is a weighted average of the RMSE values for wind speed, dewpoint
 temperature, temperature, height, and pressure at several levels in the
 atmosphere.
 The variables, levels, and lead times included in the index are shown in
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "compute_GO_Index"

\end_inset

.
 The partial sums (SL1L2 lines in the STAT output) for each of these variables
 at each level and lead time must have been computed in a previous step.
 The Stat-Analysis tool then uses the weights in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "compute_GO_Index"

\end_inset

 to compute values for the GO Index.
 For a general skill score index, the user can specify the weights and variables
 to use in the calculations.
 
\end_layout

